# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mutation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Individuals with a 16p11.2 duplication may experience intellectual impairment and developmental delay.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Roughly one-third of kids with this illness experience delays in learning motor skills like sitting, crawling, or walking.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Affected people's average IQ is roughly 26 points lower than their parents' IQ without the duplication.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Roughly 80% of individuals with a 16p11.2 duplication experience speech or language difficulties.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] It may have an impact on both receptive and expressive language abilities.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] ADHD is among the most prevalent behavioral issues linked to this chromosomal alteration.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Approximately one in five individuals with a 16p11.2 duplication are diagnosed with autism spectrum disorder, a condition that impacts social and communication abilities.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Additionally, there is a higher chance of mental health issues among affected people, such as sadness, anxiety, and schizophrenia.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] With this illness, recurrent seizures are conceivable, albeit they are uncommon in the majority of affected persons.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] A 16p11.2 duplication can also result in other problems such as renal and urinary system deformities.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] 16p11.2 duplications do not, however, exhibit a specific pattern of physical anomalies; in fact, the indications and symptoms associated with the chromosomal alteration differ even among afflicted family members.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] A genetic region on the short (p) arm of chromosome 16 at a place known as p11.2 is duplicated in individuals with a 16p11.2 duplication.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] It is sufficient for a duplication in one copy of chromosome 16 in each cell to generate the disease since 16p11.2 duplications follow an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.
[src:mutation/16p11-2-duplication-syndrome] Researchers at Northwestern University created a mouse model of the syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletion syndrome is not to be confused with 17q12 microduplication syndrome, caused by the addition of genetic material in the same region from which it is removed in the microdeletion, or with 17q21.31 microdeletion syndrome, another name for Koolen–De Vries syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions have a variable phenotype, ranging from few or no symptoms to severe disability.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The condition is thought to be underdiagnosed, and cases with milder phenotypes may not reach clinical attention unless they have an affected child themselves.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The most characteristic symptom is renal cysts and diabetes syndrome (RCAD), also known as "type 5 diabetes", which is caused by deletion of the associated HNF1B gene in the region.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] RCAD is associated with kidney abnormalities and a characteristic form of diabetes that causes atrophy of the pancreas.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] However, some people with 17q12 microdeletions have normal renal function.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] RCAD is diagnosed in approximately 40% of people with 17q12 microdeletions, usually prior to age 25, while kidney abnormalities more broadly occur in approximately 85-90%.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] People with 17q12 microdeletions have a characteristic facial phenotype, albeit a subtle one not usually obvious in daily life.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Macrocephaly is common, along with high arched eyebrows, flattening of the malar region, and epicanthic folds.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Pathological short stature is possible, and a characteristic "short and stocky" body shape occurs in many cases.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions are associated with neurocognitive and developmental involvement of variable severity.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Some have mild to moderate intellectual disability; however, such impairment is not universal.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Average intelligence is in the average to low average range.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Speech delay is common, regardless of intellectual functioning.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The most striking association between 17q12 microdeletions and neurodevelopment is the raised prevalence of autism spectrum disorder, with significant increases in both diagnosis and subclinical autistic traits.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions have been implicated as one of the major genetic causes of high-functioning autistic spectrum disorders.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Schizophrenia is also a significant psychiatric complication of 17q12 microdeletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions are estimated to occur in approximately 1 in 1,600 people with schizophrenia, compared to an estimation of below 1 in 50,000 in the general population.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Epilepsy, usually mild, occurs in approximately one-third of cases.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Reproductive system anomalies are associated with 17q12 microdeletions, particularly in females.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions have been linked to uterine malformations, most frequently Müllerian agenesis, where the uterus and part of the vaginal canal are absent.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletion syndrome is an autosomal dominant disorder, where one copy of the relevant mutation is enough to cause the condition.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Most cases are de novo, or spontaneous mutations that do not occur in the proband's parents; approximately 75% are de novo, while 25% are inherited.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] People with 17q12 microdeletions who have normal fertility have a 50% chance of passing the deletion down to their offspring.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Environmental factors have not been implicated in the syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Like other chromosomal microdeletions, 17q12 microdeletion syndrome is diagnosed via fluorescence in situ hybridization.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Traditional karyotyping, used to diagnose major chromosomal disorders such as aneuploidy, is rarely sensitive enough to detect microdeletions.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] As the underlying 17q12 microdeletion is an innate genetic disorder, it cannot by itself be treated.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Rather, treatment is symptomatic and supportive.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The high prevalence of kidney disease indicates routine monitoring of renal function, particularly in people taking potentially nephrotoxic medications such as lithium.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The prevalence of 17q12 microdeletion syndrome is unknown, and it is likely to be underdiagnosed.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microdeletions are estimated to occur in approximately 1 in 600 people on the autism spectrum and 1 in 1,600 with schizophrenia, but are far rarer in the general population.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] General prevalence is estimated to be between 1 in 14,000 and 1 in 62,500.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] In addition to the increased prevalence in autism and schizophrenia, some other clinical populations have increased prevalence of 17q12 microdeletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The condition occurs in approximately 2% of those with congenital kidney abnormalities and 3-6% of women with Müllerian agenesis.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] It is one of the ten most common microdeletions amongst children with idiopathic developmental delay.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] 17q12 microduplication syndrome is far rarer than the corresponding microdeletion, estimated to occur roughly one-fifth as frequently as 17q12 microdeletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Due to its rarity and the overlap between their phenotypes, 17q12 microduplications are usually discussed as an adjunct to microdeletions.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Like the microdeletion syndrome, the microduplication syndrome has a broad phenotypic range, ranging from asymptomatic to profound disability; intellectual disability is frequently but not always more severe than the microdeletion, while physical health is often better.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] A case of sex reversal has been reported.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] While autism comorbid with 17q12 microduplication has been reported, it appears far rarer than in the microdeletion.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] Physical anomalies associated with 17q12 microduplication syndrome include syndactyly, microcephaly, epicanthic folds, and thick eyebrows or a unibrow.
[src:mutation/17q12-microdeletion-syndrome] The 17q12 microduplication appears to have a low penetrance, as many cases are inherited from asymptomatic parents.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The condition is caused by a genetic deletion (loss of a segment of DNA) on the outermost band on the short arm (p) of chromosome 1.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] It is one of the most common deletion syndromes.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The syndrome is thought to affect one in every 5,000 to 10,000 births.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] There are a number of signs and symptoms characteristic of monosomy 1p36, but no one individual will display all of the possible features.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] In general, children will exhibit failure to thrive and global delays.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Most young children with 1p36 deletion syndrome have delayed development of speech and motor skills.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Speech is severely affected, with many children learning only a few words or having no speech at all.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Behavioral problems are also common, and include temper outbursts, banging or throwing objects, striking people, screaming episodes, and self-injurious behavior (wrist biting, head striking/banging).
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] A significant proportion of affected people are on the autism spectrum, and many exhibit stereotypy.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Most people with 1p36 deletion syndrome have some structural abnormality of the brain, and approximately half have epilepsy or other seizures.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Almost all children exhibit some degree of hypotonia.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Common structural brain abnormalities include agenesis of the corpus callosum, cerebral cortical atrophy, gait abnormalities, and ventriculomegaly.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Dysphagia, esophageal reflux, and other feeding difficulties are also common.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The most common visual abnormalities associated with 1p36 deletion syndrome include farsightedness (hypermetropia), myopia (nearsightedness), and strabismus (cross-eyes).
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Less common but still recognized are blepharophimosis, cataracts, ocular albinism, optic atrophy, optic disk pallor, and optic nerve coloboma.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The facial features of 1p36 deletion syndrome have been considered to be characteristic, although few patients have been diagnosed solely on the basis of facial appearance.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Infants may have a large anterior fontanelle, or the anterior fontanelle may close late.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Short feet, brachydactyly (short fingers), and camptodactyly (permanent flexion of a finger), fifth finger clinodactyly (abnormal curvature) and other skeletal anomalies are sometimes found in conjunction with 1p36 deletion.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] These patients may have congenital heart defects ranging from cardiac septal defects to valvular anomalies and tetralogy of Fallot.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] In particular, some of the patients may have LV noncompaction a form of dilated cardiomyopathy.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] This form of LV noncompaction cardiomyopathy is thought to be related to the deletion of the gene CASZ1, this gene in mice leads to ventricular noncompaction.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] 1p36 deletion syndrome is caused by the deletion of the most distal light band of the short arm of chromosome 1.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The breakpoints for 1p36 deletion syndrome have been variable and are most commonly found from 1p36.13 to 1p36.33.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] 40 percent of all breakpoints occur 3 to 5 million base pairs from the telomere.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] The size of the deletion ranges from approximately 1.5 million base pairs to greater than 10 million.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Most deletions in chromosome 1p36 are de novo mutations.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] 20% of patients with 1p36 deletion syndrome inherit the disease from one parent who carries a balanced or symmetrical translocation.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] 1p36 deletion syndrome is usually suspected based on the signs and symptoms and confirmed by fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH).
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Chromosomal microarray or karyotype analysis may also be used to diagnose 1p36 deletion.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] There is no cure for 1p36 deletion syndrome, and treatment is focused on relieving symptoms of the disease.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Of particular importance are appropriate medication for endocrine and neurologic manifestations, such as anti-seizure medications.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Feeding difficulties can be managed with specialized assistive devices or with a gastrostomy (feeding) tube.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] 1p36 deletion syndrome is the most common terminal deletion syndrome in humans.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] It occurs in between 1 in 5000 and 1 in 10000 live births.
[src:mutation/1p36-deletion-syndrome] Only 100 cases have been reported between 1981 and 2015.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] 1q21.1 copy number variations (CNVs) are rare aberrations of human chromosome 1.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In a common situation a human cell has one pair of identical chromosomes on chromosome 1.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] With the 1q21.1 CNVs one chromosome of the pair is not complete because a part of the sequence of the chromosome is missing, or overcomplete, because some parts of the sequence are duplicated.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The result is that one chromosome is of normal length and the other one is too long or too short.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The area has a size of approximately 6 Megabase (Mb) (from 141.5 Mb to 147.9 Mb).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Within 1q21.1 there are two areas where the CNVs can be found: the proximal area or TAR area (144.1 to 144.5) and the distal area (144.7 to 145.9).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] A 1q21.1 CNV will commonly be found in one of these areas, but an overlap with the other area or parts that are outside these areas are possible.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] 1q21.1 has multiple repetitions of the same structure: Only 25% of the structure is not duplicated.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] There is no further information available about the DNA-sequence in those areas up till now.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The gaps represent approximately 700 Kilobase.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The area of 1q21.1 is one of the most difficult parts of the human genome to map.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] CNVs occur due to non-allelic homologous recombination mediated by low copy repeats (sequentially similar regions), commonly found in 1q21.1.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Four separate forms of 1q21.1 CNVs are mentioned in literature.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The CNVs lead to a very variable phenotype and the manifestations in individuals are quite variable.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Some people who have a CNV can function in a normal way, while others have symptoms of mental retardation and various physical anomalies.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Meiosis is the process of dividing cells in humans.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In meiosis, the chromosome pairs splits and a representative of each pair goes to one daughter cell.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In this way the number of chromosomes will be halved in each cell, while all the parts on the chromosome (genes) remain, after being randomized.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Which information of the parent cell ends up in the daughter cell is purely decided by chance.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Besides this random process, there is a second random process.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In this second random process the DNA will be scrambled in a way that pieces are omitted (deletion), added (duplication), moved from one place to another (translocation) and inverted (inversion).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] This is a common process, which leads to about 0,4% variation in the DNA.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] It explains why even identical twins are not genetically 100% identical.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Problem of the second random process is that genetic mistakes can occur.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Especially due to the deletion and duplication process, the chromosomes that come together in a new cell may be shorter or longer.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] The result of this spontaneous change in the structure of DNA is a so-called copy number variation.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Due to the CNV chromosomes of different sizes can be combined in a new cell.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] If this occurs around conception, the result will be a first cell of a human with a genetic variation.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] This can be either positive or negative.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In positive cases this new human will be capable of a special skill that is assessed positively, for example, in sports or science.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] In negative cases, you have to deal with a syndrome or a severe disability, as in this case the 1q21.1 CNVs.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Based on the meiotic process, the syndrome may occur in two ways.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Due to this genetic misprint the embryo may experience problems in the development during the first months of pregnancy.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Approximately 20 to 40 days after fertilization, something goes wrong in the construction of the body parts and brain, which leads to a chain reaction.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Because of the repetitions in 1q21.1, there is a larger chance on an unequal crossing-over during meiosis.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Genes related to the proximal area are HFE2, TXNIP, POLR3GL, LIX1L, RBM8A, PEX11B, ITGA10, ANKRD35, PIAS3, NUDT17, POLR3C, RNF115, CD160, PDZK1, and GPR89A.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-copy-number-variations] Genes related to the distal area are PDE4DIP, HYDIN2, PRKAB2, PDIA3P, FMO5, CHD1L, BCL9, ACP6, GJA5, GJA8, NBPF10, GPR89B, GPR89C, PDZK1P1 and NBPF11.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] In *1q21.1* the initial '1' stands for chromosome 1, the 'q' stands for the long arm of the chromosome and '21.1' stands for the part of the long arm in which the deletion is situated.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The syndrome is a form of the 1q21.1 copy number variations, and it is a deletion in the distal area of the 1q21.1 part.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The CNV leads to a very variable phenotype, and the manifestations in individuals are quite variable.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Some people who have the syndrome can function in a normal way, while others have symptoms of intellectual impairment and various physical anomalies.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] 1q21.1 microdeletion is a very rare chromosomal condition.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] As of 2024, only 102 people with 1q21.1 deletion syndrome have been identified in medical research.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The recurrent 1q21.1 microdeletion was first identified in 2008 through a chromosomal microarray studies published in Nature Genetics and the New England Journal of Medicine.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Approximately 75% of all children with a 1q21.1 microdeletion exhibit delayed development, notably in motor skills such as sitting, standing, and walking.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Individuals may have generalized mild learning difficulties; about 30% of those diagnosed with 1q21.1 deletion syndrome are affected.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Dysmorphic craniofacial traits are common, however, they are highly varied and thus difficult to identify.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Microcephaly has been reported in 39% of those with the 1q21.1 deletion.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] It is not clear whether the list of symptoms is complete.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Very little information is known about the syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The syndrome can have completely different effects on members of the same family.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Genitourinary abnormalities include vesicoureteral reflux, hydronephrosis, inguinal hernia, cryptorchidism, and genital malformations.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] There have been two reported cases of Mayer-Rokitansky-Kuster-Hauser syndrome alongside 1q21.1 deletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The majority of affected people have normal neurologic physical examinations, however hypotonia and tremors are quite common.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Seizures affect roughly 16% of children and typically begin during infancy.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Possible psychiatric and behavioral abnormalities include autism spectrum disorder, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, and mood disorders.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Furthermore, distal 1q21.1 microdeletions have been found in 0.2%-0.6% of those with schizophrenia.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Mefford states that the standard for a deletion is 1.35Mb.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Physical and clinical features reported in individuals with the distal 1q21.1 deletion are highly variable, ranging from no apparent findings to multiple congenital and developmental differences.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Commonly affected systems include growth, neurological and motor function, heart development, vision, and behavior.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] 1q21.1 deletion is autosomal dominant, with 18%-50% of deletions developing de novo and 50%-82% inherited from a parent.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The majority of affected individuals are missing a 1.35 million DNA base pair sequence, also written as 1.35 megabases (Mb), in the q21.1 region of chromosome 1, though the exact size of the deleted region differs.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] This deletion affects one of each cell's two copies of chromosome 1.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The symptoms caused by a 1q21.1 microdeletion are most likely due to the loss of many genes in this region.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Researchers are attempting to determine which missing genes may contribute to 1q21.1 deletions' specific characteristics.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Because some people with a 1q21.1 microdeletion have no clear associated traits, it is hypothesized that additional genetic and environmental factors influence the development of symptoms.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The recurring distal 1.35-Mb heterozygous deletion within the position of 145–146.35 Mb in the reference genome confirms the diagnosis of 1q21.1 deletion.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The copy number of sequences can be determined using chromosome microarrays or targeted deletion analysis by fluorescence in situ hybridization.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] 22q11.2 microdeletion shares several characteristics with 1q21.1 microdeletion including developmental delays, learning disabilities, intellectual disability, and behavioral deviations.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Those with recurrent 1q21.1 microdeletion, on the other hand, do not have the distinctive facial traits seen in the 22q11.2 microdeletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Several examinations should be performed to determine the level of disability and the needs of a person with the 1q21.1 deletion.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Because of the vast range of symptoms, ophthalmologic, cardiac, developmental, neurological, and psychiatric evaluations may be helpful in identifying the manifestations of 1q21.1 deletion.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Different developmental abnormalities of the skull and genitourinary system can be identified with brain imaging and renal ultrasounds.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Consultations with a medical geneticist or genetic counselor can aid in determining the cause of 1q21.1 deletion.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Because of the variability in 1q21.1 deletion, management is dependent on specific symptoms.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Occupational and physical therapy, as well as special learning programs, may be used to manage symptoms.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Feeding therapy may be used to address poor growth, with a low threshold for feeding evaluation and/or radiographic swallowing study when there are clinical signs or symptoms of dysphagia.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Nonallelic homologous recombination (NAHR), mediated by low copy repeats (LCRs), is a well-known mechanism of copy number alterations in an array of genomic diseases.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Individually, these conditions are uncommon, yet collectively, they impact a significant portion of the population.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] 1q21.1 deletions are estimated to occur in about 0.015% of the population.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] However, these CNVs are incompletely penetrant, therefore it is likely that the actual prevalence in the general population is greater than the current predictions.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Statistical research showed that schizophrenia is more common in combination with 1q21.1 deletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] On the other side, autism is significantly more common with 1q21.1 duplication syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Further research confirmed that the odds on a relation between schizophrenia and deletions at 1q21.1, 3q29, 15q13.3, 22q11.21 en Neurexin 1 (NRXN1) and duplications at 16p11.2 are at 7.5% or higher.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Common variations in the BCL9 gene, which is in the distal area, confer risk of schizophrenia and may also be associated with bipolar disorder and major depressive disorder.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Research is done on 10–12 genes on 1q21.1 that produce DUF1220-locations.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] DUF1220 is an unknown protein, which is active in the neurons of the brain near the neocortex.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Based on research on apes and other mammals, it is assumed that DUF1220 is related to cognitive development (man: 212 locations; chimpanzee: 37 locations; monkey: 30 locations; mouse: 1 location).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] It appears that the DUF1220-locations on 1q21.1 are in areas that are related to the size and the development of the brain.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] The aspect of the size and development of the brain is related to autism (macrocephaly) and schizophrenia (microcephaly).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] Another relation between macrocephaly with duplications and microcephaly with deletions has been seen in research on the HYDIN Paralog or HYDIN2.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] This part of 1q21.1 is involved in the development of the brain.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] It is assumed to be a dosage-sensitive gene.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] When this gene is not available in the 1q21.1 area, it leads to microcephaly.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] HYDIN2 is a recent duplication (found only in humans) of the HYDIN gene found on 16q22.2.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] GJA5 has been identified as the gene that is responsible for the phenotypes observed with congenital heart diseases on the 1q21.1 location.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] In case of a duplication of GJA5 tetralogy of Fallot is more common.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-deletion-syndrome] In case of a deletion other congenital heart diseases than tetralogy of Fallot are more common.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Clinical signs of 1q21.1 recurrent microdeletion can vary greatly across individuals.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Developmental delay and slightly dysmorphic facial features are the most frequent symptoms.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] But this isn't a diagnosis that can be diagnosed clinically, and some people with this microdeletion don't show any clear symptoms at all.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] It is difficult to identify the dysmorphic facial traits associated with 1q21.1 microduplications.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] The findings that are most frequently recorded include frontal bossing, hypertelorism, and (relative) macrocephaly.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] About 18 and 29% of patients with proximal and distal 1q21.1 microduplications, respectively, have congenital cardiac abnormalities.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] These include a wide range of anomalies, such as Septal Defects, conotruncal, left- and right-sided defects, and other heart abnormalities.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] 1q21.1 duplication syndrome arises from microduplications of the BP3-BP4 region, containing at least seven genes and a minimum duplicated region of ~1.2 Mb of unique DNA sequence.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] 1q21.1 duplication syndrome has an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, where 18–50% of deletions happen de novo and 50–82% are inherited from their parents.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] The 1q21.1 area is one of the largest regions in the human genome with repetitive duplication, rendering it prone to copy number variation.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Because of its frequent low-copy duplications, it is thought to be the most genetically unstable fragment.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] There are two main ways that the copy number variations of 1q21.1 might appear: Type I, which spans roughly 1.8 Mb and includes only the distal end area of 1q21.1, and type 2, which extends proximally to include the thrombocytopenia absent radius syndrome region, span around 2.7 Mb.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] For children with 1q21.1 microduplication syndrome, whole exon sequencing in conjunction with quantitative polymerase chain reaction can yield a precise molecular diagnosis.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] The ratio of sexes does not significantly differ.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] About 0.03% of adults exhibit microduplication of 1q21.1, while the frequency in live births is estimated to be 1/6309.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Statistical research showed that schizophrenia is significantly more common in combination with 1q21.1 deletion syndrome.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Similar observations were done for chromosome 16 on 16p11.2 (deletion: autism/duplication: schizophrenia), chromosome 22 on 22q11.21 (deletion (Velo-cardio-facial syndrome): schizophrenia/duplication: autism) and 22q13.3 (deletion (Phelan-McDermid syndrome): schizophrenia/duplication: autism).
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] Research is done on 10-12 genes on 1q21.1 that produce DUF1220-locations.
[src:mutation/1q21-1-duplication-syndrome] When this gene is not available in the 1q21.1 area it leads to microcephaly.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Pyrene is a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon consisting of four benzene rings fused together in a planar aromatic arrangement which approximates a rhombus in shape.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Benzo[*a*]pyrene is a derivative in which a fifth benzene ring has been fused to the pyrene system, and is a component of tobacco smoke which is a procarcinogen partly responsible for the carcinogenic and mutagenic effects of smoking.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide is a metabolite of benzo[*a*]pyrene formed by the introduction of vicinal hydroxyl and epoxide functional groups to the fifth benzene ring.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] These oxidations are stereoselective, producing the pair of enantiomers with the hydroxyl groups on opposite sides of the pyrene plane and with the epoxide on the same side as its adjacent hydroxyl group.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] The metabolism of the tobacco smoke procarcinogen benzo[*a*]pyrene involves three distinct steps – the introduction of an epoxide group in the 7,8-position, its hydration to a vicinal diol and the introduction of an epoxide in the 9,10-position.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] In the first step, a cytochrome P450 1A1 (CYP1A1) catalysed oxidation produces several products including (+)-benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-epoxide.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] The enzyme epoxide hydrolase, then hydrates the epoxide ring to yield the vicinal diol (−)-benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol, which is then oxidised by cytochrome P450 oxidase again forming the mutagen and carcinogen (+)-benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Aflatoxin has a similar mechanism of action, though its binding is through the N7, rather than the N2, position of guanine.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Multiple stereochemical outcomes are possible from these transformations.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] The *anti* stereoisomer (shown here) and its enantiomer are the ultimate carcinogens from benzo[*a*]pyrene, but the *syn* isomers are also produced.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] (+)-Benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide has been shown to bind to an N2 atom of a guanine nucleobase in DNA, distorting the double helix structure by intercalation of the pyrene moiety between base pairs through π-stacking.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] There are indications that (+)-benzo[*a*]pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide specifically targets the protective p53 gene; More than 50 percent of human tumors contain a mutation or deletion of the p53 gene.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] This gene is a transcription factor that regulates the cell cycle and hence functions as a tumor suppressor.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] The *anti*-benzo[*a*]pyrene diol epoxides induce guanine to thymine transversions in related areas of p53, thereby inactivating its tumor suppression ability in certain cells, leading to genetic mutations and potentially to cancer.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] This process increases transcription of genes including CYP1A1, resulting in increased CYP1A1 protein production.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] This process is similar to induction of CYP1A1 by certain polychlorinated biphenyls and dioxins.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Seemingly, CYP1A1 activity in the intestinal mucosa prevents major amounts of ingested benzo[*a*]pyrene to enter portal blood and systemic circulation.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Intestinal, but not hepatic, expression of CYP1A1 depends on TOLL-like receptor 2 (TLR2), which is a eucaryotic receptor for bacterial surface structures such as lipoteichoic acid.
[src:mutation/benzo-a-pyrene-7-8-dihydrodiol-9-10-epoxide] Moreover, benzo[*a*]pyrene has been found to activate a transposon, LINE1, in humans.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In biology, a **mutation** is an alteration in the nucleic acid sequence of the genome of an organism, virus, or extrachromosomal DNA.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations result from errors during replication, mitosis, meiosis, or damage to DNA, which then may trigger error-prone repair or cause an error during replication (translesion synthesis).
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations may also result from substitution, insertion or deletion of segments of DNA due to mobile genetic elements.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations may or may not produce detectable changes in the observable characteristics (phenotype) of an organism.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations play a part in both normal and abnormal biological processes including: evolution, cancer, and the development of the immune system, including junctional diversity.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutation is the ultimate source of all genetic variation, providing the raw material on which evolutionary forces such as natural selection can act.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutation can result in many different types of change in sequences.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations in genes can have no effect, alter the product of a gene, or prevent the gene from functioning properly or completely.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations can also occur in non-genic regions.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutation and DNA damage are the two major types of errors that occur in DNA, but they are fundamentally different.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DNA damage is a physical alteration in the DNA structure, such as a single or double strand break, a modified guanosine residue in DNA such as 8-hydroxydeoxyguanosine, or a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon adduct.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DNA damages can be recognized by enzymes, and therefore can be correctly repaired using the complementary undamaged strand in DNA as a template or an undamaged sequence in a homologous chromosome if it is available.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] If DNA damage remains in a cell, transcription of a gene may be prevented and thus translation into a protein may also be blocked.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DNA replication may also be blocked and/or the cell may die.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In contrast to a DNA damage, a mutation is an alteration of the base sequence of the DNA.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Ordinarily, a mutation cannot be recognized by enzymes once the base change is present in both DNA strands, and thus a mutation is not ordinarily repaired.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] At the cellular level, mutations can alter protein function and regulation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Unlike DNA damages, mutations are replicated when the cell replicates.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] At the level of cell populations, cells with mutations will increase or decrease in frequency according to the effects of the mutations on the ability of the cell to survive and reproduce.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Although distinctly different from each other, DNA damages and mutations are related because DNA damages often cause errors of DNA synthesis during replication or repair and these errors are a major source of mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations can involve the duplication of large sections of DNA, usually through genetic recombination.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] These duplications are a major source of raw material for evolving new genes, with tens to hundreds of genes duplicated in animal genomes every million years.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Most genes belong to larger gene families of shared ancestry, detectable by their sequence homology.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Novel genes are produced by several methods, commonly through the duplication and mutation of an ancestral gene, or by recombining parts of different genes to form new combinations with new functions.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Here, protein domains act as modules, each with a particular and independent function, that can be mixed together to produce genes encoding new proteins with novel properties.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For example, the human eye uses four genes to make structures that sense light: three for cone cell or colour vision and one for rod cell or night vision; all four arose from a single ancestral gene.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Another advantage of duplicating a gene (or even an entire genome) is that this increases engineering redundancy; this allows one gene in the pair to acquire a new function while the other copy performs the original function.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Other types of mutation occasionally create new genes from previously noncoding DNA.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Changes in chromosome number may involve even larger mutations, where segments of the DNA within chromosomes break and then rearrange.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For example, in the Homininae, two chromosomes fused to produce human chromosome 2; this fusion did not occur in the lineage of the other apes, and they retain these separate chromosomes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In evolution, the most important role of such chromosomal rearrangements may be to accelerate the divergence of a population into new species by making populations less likely to interbreed, thereby preserving genetic differences between these populations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Sequences of DNA that can move about the genome, such as transposons, make up a major fraction of the genetic material of plants and animals, and may have been important in the evolution of genomes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For example, more than a million copies of the Alu sequence are present in the human genome, and these sequences have now been recruited to perform functions such as regulating gene expression.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Another effect of these mobile DNA sequences is that when they move within a genome, they can mutate or delete existing genes and thereby produce genetic diversity.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Nonlethal mutations accumulate within the gene pool and increase the amount of genetic variation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The abundance of some genetic changes within the gene pool can be reduced by natural selection, while other "more favorable" mutations may accumulate and result in adaptive changes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For example, a butterfly may produce offspring with new mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The majority of these mutations will have no effect; but one might change the colour of one of the butterfly's offspring, making it harder (or easier) for predators to see.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] If this color change is advantageous, the chances of this butterfly's surviving and producing its own offspring are a little better, and over time the number of butterflies with this mutation may form a larger percentage of the population.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Neutral mutations are defined as mutations whose effects do not influence the fitness of an individual.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] These can increase in frequency over time due to genetic drift.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] It is believed that the overwhelming majority of mutations have no significant effect on an organism's fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Also, DNA repair mechanisms are able to mend most changes before they become permanent mutations, and many organisms have mechanisms, such as apoptotic pathways, for eliminating otherwise-permanently mutated somatic cells.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Beneficial mutations can improve reproductive success.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Four classes of mutations are (1) spontaneous mutations (molecular decay), (2) mutations due to error-prone replication bypass of naturally occurring DNA damage (also called error-prone translesion synthesis), (3) errors introduced during DNA repair, and (4) induced mutations caused by mutagens.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Scientists may sometimes deliberately introduce mutations into cells or research organisms for the sake of scientific experimentation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] One 2017 study claimed that 66% of cancer-causing mutations are random, 29% are due to the environment (the studied population spanned 69 countries), and 5% are inherited.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Humans on average pass 60 new mutations to their children but fathers pass more mutations depending on their age with every year adding two new mutations to a child.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] There is increasing evidence that the majority of spontaneously arising mutations are due to error-prone replication (translesion synthesis) past DNA damage in the template strand.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In mice, the majority of mutations are caused by translesion synthesis.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Likewise, in yeast, Kunz et al. found that more than 60% of the spontaneous single base pair substitutions and deletions were caused by translesion synthesis.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Although naturally occurring double-strand breaks occur at a relatively low frequency in DNA, their repair often causes mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) is a major pathway for repairing double-strand breaks.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] NHEJ involves removal of a few nucleotides to allow somewhat inaccurate alignment of the two ends for rejoining followed by addition of nucleotides to fill in gaps.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] As a consequence, NHEJ often introduces mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Induced mutations are alterations in the gene after it has come in contact with mutagens and environmental causes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Whereas in former times mutations were assumed to occur by chance, or induced by mutagens, molecular mechanisms of mutation have been discovered in bacteria and across the tree of life.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The sequence of a gene can be altered in a number of ways.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Gene mutations have varying effects on health depending on where they occur and whether they alter the function of essential proteins.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations in the structure of genes can be classified into several types.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Small-scale mutations affect a gene in one or a few nucleotides.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The effect of a mutation on protein sequence depends in part on where in the genome it occurs, especially whether it is in a coding or non-coding region.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations in the non-coding regulatory sequences of a gene, such as promoters, enhancers, and silencers, can alter levels of gene expression, but are less likely to alter the protein sequence.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutations within introns and in regions with no known biological function (e.g. pseudogenes, retrotransposons) are generally neutral, having no effect on phenotype – though intron mutations could alter the protein product if they affect mRNA splicing.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A mutation becomes an effect on function mutation when the exactitude of functions between a mutated protein and its direct interactor undergoes change.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The interactors can be other proteins, molecules, nucleic acids, etc.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] There are many mutations that fall under the category of by effect on function, but depending on the specificity of the change the mutations listed below will occur.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This classification is obviously relative and somewhat artificial: a harmful mutation can quickly turn into a beneficial mutations when conditions change.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Also, there is a gradient from harmful/beneficial to neutral, as many mutations may have small and mostly neglectable effects but under certain conditions will become relevant.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Also, many traits are determined by hundreds of genes (or loci), so that each locus has only a minor effect.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For instance, human height is determined by hundreds of genetic variants ("mutations") but each of them has a very minor effect on height, apart from the impact of nutrition.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Height (or size) itself may be more or less beneficial as the huge range of sizes in animal or plant groups shows.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Attempts have been made to infer the distribution of fitness effects (DFE) using mutagenesis experiments and theoretical models applied to molecular sequence data.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DFE can also be tracked by tracking the skewness of the distribution of mutations with putatively severe effects as compared to the distribution of mutations with putatively mild or absent effect.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In summary, the DFE plays an important role in predicting evolutionary dynamics.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A variety of approaches have been used to study the DFE, including theoretical, experimental and analytical methods.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] One of the earliest theoretical studies of the distribution of fitness effects was done by Motoo Kimura, an influential theoretical population geneticist.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] His neutral theory of molecular evolution proposes that most novel mutations will be highly deleterious, with a small fraction being neutral.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A later proposal by Hiroshi Akashi proposed a bimodal model for the DFE, with modes centered around highly deleterious and neutral mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Both theories agree that the vast majority of novel mutations are neutral or deleterious and that advantageous mutations are rare, which has been supported by experimental results.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] One example is a study done on the DFE of random mutations in vesicular stomatitis virus.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Out of all mutations, 39.6% were lethal, 31.2% were non-lethal deleterious, and 27.1% were neutral.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Another example comes from a high throughput mutagenesis experiment with yeast.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In this experiment it was shown that the overall DFE is bimodal, with a cluster of neutral mutations, and a broad distribution of deleterious mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Though relatively few mutations are advantageous, those that are play an important role in evolutionary changes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Like neutral mutations, weakly selected advantageous mutations can be lost due to random genetic drift, but strongly selected advantageous mutations are more likely to be fixed.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Knowing the DFE of advantageous mutations may lead to increased ability to predict the evolutionary dynamics.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Theoretical work on the DFE for advantageous mutations has been done by John H.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] They proposed that the distribution for advantageous mutations should be exponential under a wide range of conditions, which, in general, has been supported by experimental studies, at least for strongly selected advantageous mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In general, it is accepted that the majority of mutations are neutral or deleterious, with advantageous mutations being rare; however, the proportion of types of mutations varies between species.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This indicates two important points: first, the proportion of effectively neutral mutations is likely to vary between species, resulting from dependence on effective population size; second, the average effect of deleterious mutations varies dramatically between species.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In addition, the DFE also differs between coding regions and noncoding regions, with the DFE of noncoding DNA containing more weakly selected mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Diploid organisms (e.g., humans) contain two copies of each gene—a paternal and a maternal allele.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Based on the occurrence of mutation on each chromosome, we may classify mutations into three types.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A wild type or homozygous non-mutated organism is one in which neither allele is mutated.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A germline mutation in the reproductive cells of an individual gives rise to a *constitutional mutation* in the offspring, that is, a mutation that is present in every cell.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A constitutional mutation can also occur very soon after fertilization, or continue from a previous constitutional mutation in a parent.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A germline mutation can be passed down through subsequent generations of organisms.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The distinction between germline and somatic mutations is important in animals that have a dedicated germline to produce reproductive cells.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] However, it is of little value in understanding the effects of mutations in plants, which lack a dedicated germline.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The distinction is also blurred in those animals that reproduce asexually through mechanisms such as budding, because the cells that give rise to the daughter organisms also give rise to that organism's germline.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A new germline mutation not inherited from either parent is called a ***de novo* mutation**.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A change in the genetic structure that is not inherited from a parent, and also not passed to offspring, is called a somatic mutation*.* Somatic mutations are not inherited by an organism's offspring because they do not affect the germline.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] However, they are passed down to all the progeny of a mutated cell within the same organism during mitosis.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A major section of an organism therefore might carry the same mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] These types of mutations are usually prompted by environmental causes, such as ultraviolet radiation or any exposure to certain harmful chemicals, and can cause diseases including cancer.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] With plants, some somatic mutations can be propagated without the need for seed production, for example, by grafting and stem cuttings.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] These types of mutations have led to new types of fruits, such as the "Delicious" apple and the "Washington" navel orange.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Human and mouse somatic cells have a mutation rate more than ten times higher than the germline mutation rate for both species; mice have a higher rate of both somatic and germline mutations per cell division than humans.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The disparity in mutation rate between the germline and somatic tissues likely reflects the greater importance of genome maintenance in the germline than in the soma.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This step requires a tremendous scientific effort.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Once the consensus sequence is known, the mutations in a genome can be pinpointed, described, and classified.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The committee of the Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS) has developed the standard human sequence variant nomenclature, which should be used by researchers and DNA diagnostic centers to generate unambiguous mutation descriptions.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In principle, this nomenclature can also be used to describe mutations in other organisms.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The nomenclature specifies the type of mutation and base or amino acid changes.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutation rates vary substantially across species, and the evolutionary forces that generally determine mutation are the subject of ongoing investigation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In **humans**, the mutation rate is about 50–90 *de novo* mutations per genome per generation, that is, each human accumulates about 50–90 novel mutations that were not present in their parents.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This number has been established by sequencing thousands of human trios, that is, two parents and at least one child.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The genomes of RNA viruses are based on RNA rather than DNA.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The RNA viral genome can be double-stranded (as in DNA) or single-stranded.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In some of these viruses (such as the single-stranded human immunodeficiency virus), replication occurs quickly, and there are no mechanisms to check the genome for accuracy.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This error-prone process often results in mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The rate of de novo mutations, whether germline or somatic, vary among organisms.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Individuals within the same species can even express varying rates of mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Overall, rates of de novo mutations are low compared to those of inherited mutations, which categorizes them as rare forms of genetic variation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Many observations of de novo mutation rates have associated higher rates of mutation correlated to paternal age.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In sexually reproducing organisms, the comparatively higher frequency of cell divisions in the parental sperm donor germline drive conclusions that rates of de novo mutation can be tracked along a common basis.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The frequency of error during the DNA replication process of gametogenesis, especially amplified in the rapid production of sperm cells, can promote more opportunities for de novo mutations to replicate unregulated by DNA repair machinery.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This claim combines the observed effects of increased probability for mutation in rapid spermatogenesis with short periods of time between cellular divisions that limit the efficiency of repair machinery.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Rates of de novo mutations that affect an organism during its development can also increase with certain environmental factors.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For example, certain intensities of exposure to radioactive elements can inflict damage to an organism's genome, heightening rates of mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In humans, the appearance of skin cancer during one's lifetime is induced by overexposure to UV radiation that causes mutations in the cellular and skin genome.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] There is a widespread assumption that mutations are (entirely) "random" with respect to their consequences (in terms of probability).
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This was shown to be wrong as mutation frequency can vary across regions of the genome, with such DNA repair- and mutation-biases being associated with various factors.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] For instance, Monroe and colleagues demonstrated that—in the studied plant (*Arabidopsis thaliana*)—more important genes mutate less frequently than less important ones.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] They demonstrated that mutation is "non-random in a way that benefits the plant".
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Changes in DNA caused by mutation in a coding region of DNA can cause errors in protein sequence that may result in partially or completely non-functional proteins.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Each cell, in order to function correctly, depends on thousands of proteins to function in the right places at the right times.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] When a mutation alters a protein that plays a critical role in the body, a medical condition can result.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Some mutations alter a gene's DNA base sequence but do not change the protein made by the gene.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Studies have shown that only 7% of point mutations in noncoding DNA of yeast are deleterious and 12% in coding DNA are deleterious.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The rest of the mutations are either neutral or slightly beneficial.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] If a mutation is present in a germ cell, it can give rise to offspring that carries the mutation in all of its cells.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This is the case in hereditary diseases.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] In particular, if there is a mutation in a DNA repair gene within a germ cell, humans carrying such germline mutations may have an increased risk of cancer.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] A list of 34 such germline mutations is given in the article DNA repair-deficiency disorder.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] An example of one is albinism, a mutation that occurs in the *OCA1* or *OCA2* gene.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Individuals with this disorder are more prone to many types of cancers, other disorders and have impaired vision.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DNA damage can cause an error when the DNA is replicated, and this error of replication can cause a gene mutation that, in turn, could cause a genetic disorder.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] DNA damages are repaired by the DNA repair system of the cell.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Each cell has a number of pathways through which enzymes recognize and repair damages in DNA.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Because DNA can be damaged in many ways, the process of DNA repair is an important way in which the body protects itself from disease.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Once DNA damage has given rise to a mutation, the mutation cannot be repaired.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] On the other hand, a mutation may occur in a somatic cell of an organism.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Such mutations will be present in all descendants of this cell within the same organism.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The accumulation of certain mutations over generations of somatic cells is part of cause of malignant transformation, from normal cell to cancer cell.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Cells with heterozygous loss-of-function mutations (one good copy of gene and one mutated copy) may function normally with the unmutated copy until the good copy has been spontaneously somatically mutated.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] This kind of mutation happens often in living organisms, but it is difficult to measure the rate.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Measuring this rate is important in predicting the rate at which people may develop cancer.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Point mutations may arise from spontaneous mutations that occur during DNA replication.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] The rate of mutation may be increased by mutagens.
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutagens can be physical, such as radiation from UV rays, X-rays or extreme heat, or chemical (molecules that misplace base pairs or disrupt the helical shape of DNA).
[src:mutation/mutation-p01] Mutagens associated with cancers are often studied to learn about cancer and its prevention.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Although mutations that cause changes in protein sequences can be harmful to an organism, on occasions the effect may be positive in a given environment.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In this case, the mutation may enable the mutant organism to withstand particular environmental stresses better than wild-type organisms, or reproduce more quickly.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In these cases a mutation will tend to become more common in a population through natural selection.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] That said, the same mutation can be beneficial in one condition and disadvantageous in another condition.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] By introducing novel genetic qualities to a population of organisms, de novo mutations play a critical role in the combined forces of evolutionary change.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] However, the weight of genetic diversity generated by mutational change is often considered a generally "weak" evolutionary force.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Although the random emergence of mutations alone provides the basis for genetic variation across all organic life, this force must be taken in consideration alongside all evolutionary forces at play.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Spontaneous de novo mutations as cataclysmic events of speciation depend on factors introduced by natural selection, genetic flow, and genetic drift.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] For example, smaller populations with heavy mutational input (high rates of mutation) are prone to increases of genetic variation which lead to speciation in future generations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In contrast, larger populations tend to see lesser effects of newly introduced mutated traits.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In these conditions, selective forces diminish the frequency of mutated alleles, which are most often deleterious, over time.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Compensated pathogenic deviations refer to amino acid residues in a protein sequence that are pathogenic in one species but are wild type residues in the functionally equivalent protein in another species.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Although the amino acid residue is pathogenic in the first species, it is not so in the second species because its pathogenicity is compensated by one or more amino acid substitutions in the second species.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The compensatory mutation can occur in the same protein or in another protein with which it interacts.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] It is critical to understand the effects of compensatory mutations in the context of fixed deleterious mutations due to the population fitness decreasing because of fixation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Effective population size refers to a population that is reproducing.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] An increase in this population size has been correlated with a decreased rate of genetic diversity.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The position of a population relative to the critical effect population size is essential to determine the effect deleterious alleles will have on fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] If the population is below the critical effective size fitness will decrease drastically, however if the population is above the critical effect size, fitness can increase regardless of deleterious mutations due to compensatory alleles.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] As the function of a RNA molecule is dependent on its structure, the structure of RNA molecules is evolutionarily conserved.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Therefore, any mutation that alters the stable structure of RNA molecules must be compensated by other compensatory mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In the context of RNA, the sequence of the RNA can be considered as ' genotype' and the structure of the RNA can be considered as its 'phenotype'.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Since RNAs have relatively simpler composition than proteins, the structure of RNA molecules can be computationally predicted with high degree of accuracy.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Because of this convenience, compensatory mutations have been studied in computational simulations using RNA folding algorithms.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Compensatory mutations can be explained by the genetic phenomenon epistasis whereby the phenotypic effect of one mutation is dependent upon mutation(s) at other loci.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] While epistasis was originally conceived in the context of interaction between different genes, intragenic epistasis has also been studied recently.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Existence of compensated pathogenic deviations can be explained by 'sign epistasis', in which the effects of a deleterious mutation can be compensated by the presence of an epistatic mutation in another loci.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] For a given protein, a deleterious mutation (D) and a compensatory mutation (C) can be considered, where C can be in the same protein as D or in a different interacting protein depending on the context.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The fitness effect of C itself could be neutral or somewhat deleterious such that it can still exist in the population, and the effect of D is deleterious to the extent that it cannot exist in the population.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] However, when C and D co-occur together, the combined fitness effect becomes neutral or positive.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Thus, compensatory mutations can bring novelty to proteins by forging new pathways of protein evolution : it allows individuals to travel from one fitness peak to another through the valleys of lower fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] 2005 outlined two models to explain the dynamics of compensatory pathogenic deviations (CPD).
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In the first hypothesis P is a pathogenic amino acid mutation that and C is a neutral compensatory mutation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Under these conditions, if the pathogenic mutation arises after a compensatory mutation, then P can become fixed in the population.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The second model of CPDs states that P and C are both deleterious mutations resulting in fitness valleys when mutations occur simultaneously.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Using publicly available, Ferrer-Costa et al.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] 2007 obtained compensatory mutations and human pathogenic mutation datasets that were characterized to determine what causes CPDs.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Results indicate that the structural constraints and the location in protein structure determine whether compensated mutations will occur.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Lunzer et al. tested the outcome of swapping divergent amino acids between two orthologous proteins of isopropylmalate dehydrogenase (IMDH).
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] They substituted 168 amino acids in *Escherichia coli* IMDH that are wild type residues in IMDH *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] They found that over one third of these substitutions compromised IMDH enzymatic activity in the *Escherichia coli* genetic background.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] This demonstrated that identical amino acid states can result in different phenotypic states depending on the genetic background.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] 2011 demonstrated how *Staphylococcus aureus* was able to grow normally without the presence of lipoteichoic acid due to compensatory mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Whole genome sequencing results revealed that when Cyclic-di-AMP phosphodiesterase (GdpP) was disrupted in this bacterium, it compensated for the disappearance of the cell wall polymer, resulting in normal cell growth.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Research has shown that bacteria can gain drug resistance through compensatory mutations that do not impede or having little effect on fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] 2006 has found that laboratory grown *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* strains with rifampicin resistance have reduced fitness, however drug resistant clinical strains of this pathogenic bacteria do not have reduced fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] 2012 used whole genome comparisons between clinical strains and lab derived mutants to determine the role and contribution of compensatory mutations in drug resistance to rifampicin.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Genome analysis reveal rifampicin resistant strains have a mutation in rpoA and rpoC.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] A similar study investigated the bacterial fitness associated with compensatory mutations in rifampin resistant *Escherichia coli*.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Results obtained from this study demonstrate that drug resistance is linked to bacterial fitness as higher fitness costs are linked to greater transcription errors.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Gong et al. collected obtained genotype data of influenza nucleoprotein from different timelines and temporally ordered them according to their time of origin.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Then they isolated 39 amino acid substitutions that occurred in different timelines and substituted them in a genetic background that approximated the ancestral genotype.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] They found that 3 of the 39 substitutions significantly reduced the fitness of the ancestral background.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Compensatory mutations are new mutations that arise and have a positive or neutral impact on a populations fitness.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Previous research has shown that populations have can compensate detrimental mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Burch and Chao tested Fisher's geometric model of adaptive evolution by testing whether bacteriophage φ6 evolves by small steps.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Their results showed that bacteriophage φ6 fitness declined rapidly and recovered in small steps .
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Viral nucleoproteins have been shown to avoid cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs) through arginine-to glycine substitutions.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] This substitution mutations impacts the fitness of viral nucleoproteins, however compensatory co-mutations impede fitness declines and aid the virus to avoid recognition from CTLs.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Mutations can have three different effects; mutations can have deleterious effects, some increase fitness through compensatory mutations, and lastly mutations can be counterbalancing resulting in compensatory neutral mutations.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] In the human genome, the frequency and characteristics of de novo mutations have been studied as important contextual factors to our evolution.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Compared to the human reference genome, a typical human genome varies at approximately 4.1 to 5.0 million loci, and the majority of this genetic diversity is shared by nearly 0.5% of the population.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The typical human genome also contains 40,000 to 200,000 rare variants observed in less than 0.5% of the population that can only have occurred from at least one de novo germline mutation in the history of human evolution.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] De novo mutations have also been researched as playing a crucial role in the persistence of genetic disease in humans.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] With recents advancements in next-generation sequencing (NGS), all types of de novo mutations within the genome can be directly studied, the detection of which provides a magnitude of insight toward the causes of both rare and common genetic disorders.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] Currently, the best estimate of the average human germline SNV mutation rate is 1.18 x 10^-8, with an approximate ~78 novel mutations per generation.
[src:mutation/mutation-p02] The ability to conduct whole genome sequencing of parents and offspring allows for the comparison of mutation rates between generations, narrowing down the origin possibilities of certain genetic disorders.
